    <h2 id="ordering">Ordering Phrases</h2>
    <p><strong>菜单 (càidān)</strong> — menu. <strong>我要这个 (wǒ yào zhège)</strong> — I want this one. <strong>买单 (mǎidān)</strong> — the bill please. <strong>不要辣 (bú yào là)</strong> — no spice please. These four phrases alone will get you through most restaurant situations.</p>

    <h2 id="staples">Staple Foods</h2>
    <p><strong>米饭 (mǐfàn)</strong> rice, <strong>面条 (miàntiáo)</strong> noodles, <strong>饺子 (jiǎozi)</strong> dumplings, <strong>包子 (bāozi)</strong> steamed buns, <strong>馒头 (mántou)</strong> plain steamed bread. In Taiwan, you will also encounter <strong>滷肉飯 (lǔròu fàn)</strong> braised pork rice and <strong>牛肉麵 (niúròu miàn)</strong> beef noodle soup — two beloved national dishes.</p>

    <h2 id="dishes">Popular Dishes</h2>
    <p><strong>宫保鸡丁 (gōngbǎo jīdīng)</strong> Kung Pao chicken, <strong>麻婆豆腐 (mápó dòufu)</strong> Mapo tofu, <strong>红烧肉 (hóngshāo ròu)</strong> red-braised pork, <strong>炒饭 (chǎofàn)</strong> fried rice, <strong>火锅 (huǒguō)</strong> hotpot. Each region has specialties — Sichuan for spicy, Cantonese for dim sum, Shanghai for sweet savory.</p>

    <h2 id="drinks">Drinks</h2>
    <p><strong>水 (shuǐ)</strong> water, <strong>茶 (chá)</strong> tea, <strong>咖啡 (kāfēi)</strong> coffee, <strong>啤酒 (píjiǔ)</strong> beer, <strong>珍珠奶茶 (zhēnzhū nǎichá)</strong> bubble tea — arguably Taiwan's most famous culinary export. Use our <a href="/chinese/tools/pinyin-converter/">Pinyin Converter</a> to check pronunciation of any food term.</p>

